<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-147-756  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 147 756.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Communications News  Jan 1990 v27 n1 p49(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>GSA uses fiber to speed costing. (General Services Administrationretooling National Capitol Region cost-tracking system)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Jesitus, John.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US General Services Administration upgrades its data networkwith 10M-bps fiber-optic links to increase speed and reliability.andO;The agency, whose 47-node network more than doubled in size in1989, has retooled from a bus to a star topology and migrated toan SQLBase Server data base.andP;  The data base software runs on theagency's existing equipment and gives the appearance of amulti-user network in a single-user setting.andP;  It provides fullStructured Query Language support and a user-friendly interfacethat has reduced human error.andP;  GSA officials say that the starnetwork is more reliable than a bus network because it hasmultiple hubs and less space between nodes.andP;  A central header hubwill feed smaller star networks in division offices, allowingintra-office communications even if the fiber backbone is damaged.andO;Many divisional GSA networks communicate over twisted-pairtelephone wire.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Product:   SQLBase Server (Data base management system) (usage).andO;Topic:     Fiber opticsUnited States. General Services AdministrationData CommunicationsData Base ServersGovernment AgencyUpgradingNetwork ArchitectureStar NetworksCase Study.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>